05178nam a22007575i 9780231551618DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20212021nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2020040238  a97802315516187 a10.7312/grah196042doi  a(DE-B1597)566391  a(OCoLC)1159872556  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aQP357.5 7aSCI0890002bisacsh04a612.8/2332231 aGraham, Daniel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut13aAn Internet in Your Head :bA New Paradigm for How the Brain Works /cDaniel Graham. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource :b42 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface -- t1 The Internet-Brain and the Computer-Brain -- t2 Metaphors for the Brain -- t3 What We Don’t Know About Brains -- t4 From Connectomics to Dynomics -- t5 How the Internet Works -- t6 The Internet Metaphor: First Steps to a New Theory of the Brain -- t7 Critique of the Internet Metaphor -- t8 The Internet Metaphor in Action: Emerging Models and New Technologies -- t9 The Internet Metaphor, AI, and Us -- tAfterword -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhether we realize it or not, we think of our brains as computers. In neuroscience, the metaphor of the brain as a computer has defined the field for much of the modern era. But as neuroscientists increasingly reevaluate their assumptions about how brains work, we need a new metaphor to help us ask better questions.The computational neuroscientist Daniel Graham offers an innovative paradigm for understanding the brain. He argues that the brain is not like a single computer—it is a communication system, like the internet. Both are networks whose power comes from their flexibility and reliability. The brain and the internet both must route signals throughout their systems, requiring protocols to direct messages from just about any point to any other. But we do not yet understand how the brain manages the dynamic flow of information across its entire network. The internet metaphor can help neuroscience unravel the brain’s routing mechanisms by focusing attention on shared design principles and communication strategies that emerge from parallel challenges. Highlighting similarities between brain connectivity and the architecture of the internet can open new avenues of research and help unlock the brain’s deepest secrets.An Internet in Your Head presents a clear-eyed and engaging tour of brain science as it stands today and where the new paradigm might take it next. It offers anyone with an interest in brains a transformative new way to conceptualize what goes on inside our heads.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCommunication. 0aComputational neurosciencexResearch. 0aNeural networks (Neurobiology) 0aNeural networks (Neurobiology). 0aNeurobiologyxMathematical models. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Neuroscience.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073907708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Medicine and Life Sciences 2021 Englishz978311075414808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Medicine and Life Sciences 2021z9783110753912oZDB-23-DPM40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/grah1960440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231551618423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231551618/origi